%T A395117 152414489607239,233813554207802848,106334007666823034068337913857,
%U A395117 13141823424965839183792159,270562803229847839097375413809388241,1759320844246338899352767593027632869971
%N A395117 Absolute norms of finite mock theta sums S_p(zeta_p), where p runs through the odd primes.
%C A395117 This is a companion to A394831, replacing the squared denominator (-z;z)_m^2 by the first power (-z;z)_m. The terms were computed by exact arithmetic in Q(zeta_p), not by numerical approximation. For odd prime p, each factor 1 + zeta_p^j, 1 <= j <= p-1, is a cyclotomic unit, since Norm(1 + zeta_p^j) = Phi_p(-1) = 1.
%C A395117 Therefore S_p(zeta_p) is an algebraic integer, and its norm is an integer. A direct reduction modulo (1 - zeta_p) gives S_p(zeta_p) == 1 mod (1 - zeta_p), and the computed terms satisfy a(n) == 1 mod p for 1 <= n <= 14. Empirical observation: for 1 <= n <= 14, every odd rational prime ell dividing a(n) satisfies ell == 1 mod 2*p. Unlike A394831, this sequence is not always squarefree: a(8) = 47^3 * 139 * 9293 * 20287.
%H A395117 Kathrin Bringmann and Larry Rolen, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1186/s40687-015-0035-8">Radial limits of mock theta functions</a>, Research in the Mathematical Sciences, Vol. 2, No. 1 (2015), Article 17.
%H A395117 Amanda Folsom, Ken Ono, and Robert C. Rhoades, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1017/fmp.2013.3">Mock theta functions and quantum modular forms</a>, Forum of Mathematics, Pi, Vol. 1, Cambridge University Press (2013), e2.
%F A395117 a(n) = abs(Norm_{Q(zeta_p)/Q}(S_p(zeta_p))) where S_p(z) = Sum_{m=0..p-1} z^(m^2) / Product_{j=1..m} (1 + z^j) with p = prime(n+1), and zeta_p = exp(2PiI/p). Equivalently a(n) = abs(Resultant(Phi_p(x), V_p(x))) where V_p(x) is the unique polynomial of degree < p-1 representing S_p(x) modulo Phi_p(x), and the denominators are inverted modulo Phi_p(x).
%e A395117 For n = 1, p = 3. We have S_3(zeta_3) = 2 + 2*zeta_3, so a(1) = abs(Norm(2 + 2*zeta_3)) = 4.
%e A395117 For n = 2, p = 5. We have S_5(zeta_5) = zeta_5 - zeta_5^2 + zeta_5^3, whose norm has absolute value 1, so a(2) = 1.
%e A395117 For n = 3, p = 7. We have a(3) = 449, which is prime and satisfies 449 == 1 mod 14.
%e A395117 For n = 4, p = 11. We have a(4) = 3389, which is prime and satisfies 3389 == 1 mod 22.
%o A395117 (SageMath)
%o A395117 from sage.all import *
%o A395117 def a(n):
%o A395117     p = nth_prime(n + 1)  # n=1 gives p=3.
%o A395117     K = CyclotomicField(p)
%o A395117     z = K.gen()
%o A395117     S = K(0)
%o A395117     poch = K(1)
%o A395117     for m in range(p):
%o A395117         if m > 0:
%o A395117             poch *= 1 + z^m
%o A395117         S += z^(m*m) / poch
%o A395117     return ZZ(abs(S.norm(QQ)))
%o A395117 print([a(n) for n in range(1, 15)])
%Y A395117 Cf. A065091, A393567, A394831.
%K A395117 nonn
